		<address>Christina Hallalulu</address>
		<time datetime="2014-07-26">2014-07-26</time>
		<aside>
			Whoever said cheesecake had to be unhealthy? 
			Try this sugar-free, low-carb, and high-protein indulgence!
		</aside>
	</header>
	<a id="image1" href="#recipe"><img src="article002a.jpg" /></a>
	<a id="image2" href="#recipe"><img src="article002b.jpg" /></a>
	<a id="image3" href="#recipe"><img src="article002c.jpg" /></a>
	<section id="recipe">
		<p>
			For as long as I can remember, I have had a love-hate relationship
			with cheesecake; love, because, well, what's not to love about
			something so deliciously sweet, rich and creamy combined with that
			perfect bite of crunchyiness from the graham cracker-base? 
			But the price of this would inevtiably be an expanding waistline
			and feeling stuffed for the next 24-hours. 
			Thus hate, because of the perpetual trade-off.  
		</p>
		<table class="ingredients">
			<caption>Base ingredients</caption>
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th class="amount" colspan="2">amount</th>
					<th class="name">name</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount" data-lilachop-amount="2"></td>
				<td class="unit">tbsp</td>
				<td class="name">
					light tahini, <span class="altor">or</span>
				</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="alt amount" data-lilachop-amount="2"></td>
				<td class="alt unit">tbsp</td>
				<td class="alt name">almond butter</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount" data-lilachop-amount="0.5"></td>
				<td class="unit">cup</td>
				<td class="name">ground almonds</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount" data-lilachop-amount="1"></td>
				<td class="unit">tbsp</td>
				<td class="name">
					agave syrup, <span class="altor">or</span>
				</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="alt amount" data-lilachop-amount="1"></td>
				<td class="alt unit">tbsp</td>
				<td class="alt name">honey</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
		<p>	
			Imagine my astonishment when I discovered that it is possible to
			have your cake and eat it too. 
			This recipe will tell you how. 
		</p>
		<table class="ingredients">
			<caption>Cheesecake ingredients</caption>
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th class="amount" colspan="2">amount</th>
					<th class="name">name</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount" data-lilachop-amount="170"></td>
				<td class="unit">g</td>
				<td class="name">2% Total Greek yoghurt (1 pot)</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount" data-lilachop-amount="250"></td>
				<td class="unit">g</td>
				<td class="name">quark</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount" data-lilachop-amount="1">1</td>
				<td class="unit">scoop</td>
				<td class="name">vanilla whey protein powder (I used 
					<a href="http://www.amazon.com/dp/B00FPQUNOW/?tag=lich048-20" class="amazon">Dymatize ISO 100 Hydrolyzed 100% whey gourmet vanilla</a>)
				</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount" data-lilachop-amount="0.25"></td>
				<td class="unit">cup</td>
				<td class="name">liquid egg whites (<span data-lilachop-amount="2"></span> egg whites)</td>
			</tr>
			
			<tr>
				<td class="amount" data-lilachop-amount="40"></td>
				<td class="unit">g</td>
				<td class="name">bitter dark Chocolate (I used 
					<a href="http://www.amazon.com/dp/B0059X9C7K/?tag=lich048-20" class="amazon">Lindt 90%</a>)
				</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
		<div class="servings">
			Change servings: 
			<input id="servings" type="number" min="0" step="1" value="1" onchange="changeservings(this.value);" />
		</div>
		<p>
			This recipe was adapted from 
			<a href="http://proteinpow.com/2013/08/dark-chocolate-almond-whey-protein.html">Proteinpow</a> 
			by Anna Sward, who said <q>It's as close to protein magic as one can get.</q> 
			Let's see if you agree!
		</p>
		<table id="steps">
			<caption>Steps</caption>
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th class="amount" colspan="2">time</th>
					<th>instruction</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount"></td>
				<td class="unit"></td>
				<td>Mix all the base ingredients together in a bowl.</td> 
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount"></td>
				<td class="unit"></td>
				<td> Form base layer by pressing the mix evenly down into a small pan.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount"></td>
				<td class="unit"></td>
				<td>Mix all the chesecake ingredients in a bowl.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount"></td>
				<td class="unit"></td>
				<td>Pour the cheesecake filling into the pan ontop of the
					base.</td> </tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount">30-45</td>
				<td class="unit">min</td>
				<td>
					Bake at 160'C (320'F). Be careful not to overbake
					cheesecake! It will harden as it cools, so you
					want it to still be mushy and wobbly inside when
					you remove it from the oven.
				</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount"></td>
				<td class="unit"></td>
				<td>
					Whilst the cheesecake is cooling, melt the dark
					chocolate in a bain-maire or microwave (careful
					not to let it burn), and drizzle on top of
					cheesecake.
				</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="amount"></td>
				<td class="unit"></td>
				<td>Devour immediately.</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
		<p>
			This recipe makes three slices, and macro-nutrient information is
			per slice. (Careful not to eat all 3 at once!) 
		</p>
		<p> 
			To make the recipe leaner, simply use 0% Greek yoghurt, less
			chocolate and sugar-free syrup instead of honey or agave. 
		</p>
